 CVN 75 Basic Construction/Conversion increase is driven primarily by project duration ($90M); projected wage rates, overhead, and material of the shipbuilder as estimated by the government cost estimator
 ($1,102.752M); restoration of FY25 congressional mark ($250M); rescreening of Ship's Force work to private industry aligning with Quality of Service directives ($125M); CVN-68 Class Main Engine repairs
 ($53.3M); and Workforce Development Incentives ($8.75M). The execution contract is planned to begin September 2026. The project scope and duration exceed the notional RCOH due to the ship's overall
 condition, including the largest-ever tank package. The Main Engine Repair estimate includes material and labor costs to repair and overhaul four main engines, which was not previously planned for CVN 75
 RCOH. The Workforce Development Incentive supports improvement of Shipbuilder recruitment, training, and retention of a skilled workforce resulting in increased shipyard capacity and productivity.
 CVN 74 Propulsion Equipment revised to reflect actual costs incurred. CVN 75 Propulsion Equipment increase is due to the contractor's cost revision.

 Non-nuclear government furnished equipment (GFE) is captured in Electronics, HM&E, and Ordnance. The GFE Governance Program was initiated to target soft costs by challenging performers to achieve
 savings in program management, system engineering, and logistics support. Procurement details are recorded and reviewed annually to refine and adjust estimates for required products and services to the most
 current data available. See further details in respective P-8a and P-35 exhibits. CVN 75 RCOH Ordnance Costs increase is due to additional requirements that must complete before the start of construction to
 support an on-time RCOH and funding increase is required to install SEWIP Block 3, AN/SLQ-32(V)7 system on CVN 75.

 Other Cost increase is for Quality of Service (QoS) initiatives. Off-ship housing for all Sailors assigned that normally live aboard the vessel and do not receive Basic Allowance for Housing is budgeted for
 the entire duration of the RCOH (78 months for CVN 74, 62 months for CVN 75) regardless of rank. CVN 74 Plan Costs reflect actual costs incurred. CVN 75 RCOH Plan Costs increase is due to additional
 engineering requirements that must complete before the start of construction to support an on-time RCOH.

 Less Previously Appropriated Prior Year OPN FY 2004 and FY 2005 includes the FY 2004 OPN ($234.028M) and FY 2005 OPN ($247.761M) funding supporting the reactor power units and reactor components
 for CVN 74.




