 Description:
 DESCRIPTION/JUSTIFICATION: The MH-60R provides persistent distributed, integrated, and maneuverable capabilities in the support of the Navy's Fleet Design and Distributed Maritime Operations concepts
 through its primary missions: Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW), Surface Warfare (SUW), Electronic Warfare (EW), Command and Control (CC), and Non-Combat Operations NCO). Secondary missions include:
 Amphibious Warfare (AMW), Air Warfare (AW), Health Services (HS), Fleet Support - Operations (FS-O), Intelligence Operations (INT), Logistics (LOG), and Naval Special Warfare (NSW).

 This OSIP funds modifications to the MH-60R Series aircraft to include airframe structures, avionics, weapons and mission systems.

 The land-based Precision Approach Radar (PAR) is the only precision approach available to the MH-60R and is slated to be replaced by Joint Precision Approach Landing System (JPALS) at Naval Air Stations.
 The Very high frequency Omnidirectional Radio range (VOR) navigation capability included with the Instrument Landing System (ILS) system provides instrument navigation after disestablishment of Tactical Air
 Command and Navigation system in the Continental United States. ILS provides precision approach capability ashore and to supplement currently available military PAR controlled approaches.

 Oil Filter Access Modification relocates the oil filter access for the main gearbox. Provides major reliability and safety upgrade while eliminating resonance and vibration failures.

 Digital Magnetic Anomaly Detector (DMAD) allows MH-60R to passively detect underwater magnetic anomalies (submarines) in the absence of external cueing, rapidly compressing the ASW kill chain with an
 inflight, ground truth location of an adversary submarine providing a highly accurate weapons quality track for torpedo employment. This non-acoustic detection capability paces continued improvements by peer
 adversaries in reducing submarine acoustic signatures, while also preserving aircraft counter-detection and sonobuoy expenditures.

 Minotaur is a government owned common software framework consisting of multiple services (interfaces, data management, sensor exploitation, multi-source/platform correlation/fusion, and display). Minotaur
 underpins the USN/USMC/USCG cross-platform, cross-domain multi-intelligence (multi-INT) data collection, correlation and dissemination process. Minotaur enables high bandwidth communication for robust
 cross-platform sharing and improves track quality to support Long Range Fires. FY 2026 funds the initial procurement of 40 Minotaur kits, developed from prototypes, in limited quantity to continue to meet
 operational requirements from numbered Fleets.

 ELINT Modernization Upgrade (EMU) is a government developed capability that rapidly delivers modern EW capability (signal detection and geolocation) to the MH-60R that detects, locates, and identifies
 complex and continuous wave signals from modern threat emitters enabling passive targeting supporting long range fire kill chains and Distributed Maritime Operations. FY 2026 funds the initial procurement of
 EMU kits, developed from prototypes, in limited quantity to continue to meet operational requirements from numbered Fleets.




